@zkamvar That's not weird, it's exactly what I said would happen. Twice. PR #221 has to be approved first because the linter gets very unhappy if you try to link to a nonexistent term. But I thought the term ought to be linked, so I went ahead and added that to save us all another PR for the one thing.

> Add internal links and capitalise Python (because it is capitalised throughout the document). Note: Adding the link for function will mean this does not pass the linter until PR #221 is merged.

> Can you approve that so that this can retain the internal link for function and pass all checks?

@zkamvar  I agree that it's not clear. And if I hadn't had dealings with the linter on my first PR because I tried adding internal links to things I was sure were in the glossary, but in fact were not, I would have been confused, too.

But actually, that's maybe not the only issue here? It looks like this version of `glossary.yml` might have been based on another branch? It has an entry for Hebrew, which is throwing the `Unknown keys in absolute_row_number: {'he'}` error, because `'he'` has not been included in `utils/check-glossary.py` as a valid language key.

I don't remember if an entry that only consists of a slug will pass at this point; something with this has changed recently. If not, then all of those other errors will need to be dealt with, too.

